        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This form of worshipping was so firmly rooted among the Israelites that we read of it constantly down to the reign of Josiah, by whom at length it appears to have been put down (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for Chemosh, the abomination of Moab",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Chemosh, though generally called the national god of the Moabites, is said (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 11:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to have been also the god of the Ammonites. He is first mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The worship now introduced into Jerusalem by Solomon was put down by Josiah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There is nothing in any of the Biblical notices to guide us to an opinion either about the meaning of the name or the nature of the worship offered to Chemosh. An ancient Jewish tradition relates that Chemosh was worshipped under the form of a black star, hence some have identified him with Saturn. But this is no more than conjecture. Milton alludes to the identification of Chemosh with Baal-peor:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
