      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The last words allude to a name given to this height in consequence of these buildings, ‘Mons offensionis.’ This name is said (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Dictionary of Bible",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 11. 627) to be of late origin. But the words occur in the Vulgate (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ‘ad dexteram partem montis offensionis.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and for Molech",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] See above on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Milcom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The LXX. translates the proper name, and reads ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ τῷ βασιλεῖ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Milton also reminds us that the word could be translated:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "‘First Moloch, horrid ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", besmeared with blood",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of human sacrifice, and parents’ tears",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Though for the noise of drums and timbrels loud",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Their children’s cries unheard.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The allusion in the last words is to the name ‘Tophet,’ as the valley of the son of Hinnom was called where the Moloch-worship went on. This was thought by some to be derived from the Hebrew word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "תף",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "toph",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") a timbrel. Hence the tradition of drums beaten to drown the cries of the suffering children. There is no warrant for the derivation, nor probably for the tradition. On the whole subject, see Selden, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "de Dis Syris",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 172.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Then did Solomon build an high place",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [see on 1 Kings 3:2] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "for Chemosh, the abomination of Moab",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [The meaning of \"Chemosh\" is uncertain. Gesenius suggests \"Vanquisher\" - Chemosh was the god of war. The mention of Ashtar-Chemosh on the Moabite stone \"connects the Moabite religion with the Phoenician,\" where Ashtar is the masculine form of Astarte, and suggests that \"Chemosh was connected with the androgynous deities of Phoenicia\" (Speaker's Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is probable, in fact, that Chemosh, Baal, Ashtoreth, Molech, etc., were originally so many names of the one supreme God, worshipped under different attributes, and with various rites in different countries], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "in the hill that is before Jerusalem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The hill is of course the mount of Olives. The altar would seem to have stood on the south peak, which is now known, as it has been for centuries past, as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Mons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Scandali",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Mons Offensionis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the Vulg. rendering of 2 Kings ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "l",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) See Robinson, 1:565, 566], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and for Molech, the abomination of the children of Ammon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Ewald sees in these altars a wise religious tolerance (\"Hist. Israel,\" 3. pp. 297, 298).] 1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He walked after the Ashtaroth, etc. According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the idolatry here condemned consisted in the fact that he built altars to the deities of all his foreign wives, upon which they offered incense and sacrifice to their idols. It is not stated that he himself also offered sacrifice to these idols. But even the building of altars for idols was a participation in idolatry which was irreconcilable with true fidelity to the Lord. עשׁתּרת, Astarte, was the chief female deity of all the Canaanitish tribes; her worship was also transplanted from Tyre to Carthage, where it flourished greatly. She was a moon-goddess, whom the Greeks and Romans called sometimes Aphrodite, sometimes Urania, Σεληναίη, Coelestis, and Juno (see the Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). מלכּם, which is called מלך (without the article) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and מלכּם in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 49:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 49:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 1:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the abomination of the Ammonites, must not be confounded with the Molech (המּלך, always with the article) of the early Canaanites, to whom children were offered in sacrifice in the valley of Benhinnom from the time of Ahaz onwards (see the Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), since they had both of them their separate places of worship in Jerusalem (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and nothing is ever said about the offering of children in sacrifice to Milcom; although the want of information prevents us from determining the precise distinction between the two. Milcom was at any rate related to the Chemosh of the Moabites mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for Chemosh is also described as a god of the Ammonites in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 11:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", whereas everywhere else he is called the god of the Moabites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 1:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Chemosh was a sun-god, who was worshipped as king of his people and as a god of war, and as such is depicted upon coins with a sword, lance, and shield in his hands, and with two torches by his side (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The enumeration of the different idols is incomplete; Chemosh being omitted in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Astarte, to whom Solomon also built an altar in Jerusalem, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Still this incompleteness does not warrant our filling up the supposed gaps by emendations of the text. וגו/ .txe הרע ויּעשׂ, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 2:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. יי אהרי מלּא, a pregnant expression for יי אח ללכת מלּא, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 14:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:11-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. - These places of sacrifice (בּמה, see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Solomon built upon the mountain in front, i.e., to the east, of Jerusalem, and, according to the more precise account in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to the right, that is to say, on the southern side, of the Mount of Corruption, - in other words, upon the southern peak of the Mount of Olives; and consequently this peak has been called in church tradition from the time of Brocardus onwards, either Mons Offensionis, after the Vulgate rendering of המּשׁחית הר in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or Mons Scandali, Mount of Offence (vid., Rob. Pal. i. 565 and 566).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]